	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The board may not have actual SRAM on it. I'm not sure but just because a game has WRAM, doesn't mean it's the type of RAM known as SRAM which is used with a battery to always maintain power.</div>
<br />The boards are built to take a standard 6264 SRAM. There are two kinds of RAM that can do that: SRAM and PSRAM. PSRAM is DRAM with a controller that makes it looks like SRAM to the host system. Some PSRAMs have a battery-backed "standby mode" that refreshes the RAM automatically while drawing reduced power; others don't.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


